  "text": "Sequence analysis of the inserts in the 52 plasmid clones revealed that DNA originating from seven different regions of the Salmonella chromosome could confer Fe(III) resistance upon the DpmrAB mutant (Fig. S1 ). These inserts encompassed a total of 16 open reading frames (ORFs), which were individually subcloned into (Fig. S2) . We focused our attention on the pmrC and pmrG genes because they bestowed the highest levels of Fe(III) resistance upon the DpmrAB mutant (Fig.  S2 ), and because they were known to be directly regulated by the PmrA protein [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ; this is in contrast to the six other genes, whose expression was not PmrA-dependent (data not shown). (Table 1 ). This was also true for a strain deleted for the pmrC, ugd, pmrG and yibD genes (Table 1) , which is consistent with the fact that the proteins encoded by the ugd gene and pbgP operon participate in the same pathway of synthesis and incorporation of 4-aminoarabinose into lipid A [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . We investigated all possible combinations of double and triple mutants with deletions in the pmrC, ugd, pmrG and yibD genes and determined that only the DpmrC ugd pmrG triple mutant was as hypersensitive to Fe(III) as the DpmrAB mutant (Table 1) . Furthermore, a strain deleted for of all three pmrC, ugd and pmrG genes and harbouring the pmrA505 allele, which encodes a PmrA protein that promotes transcription of PmrA-activated genes even under noninducing conditions , was as susceptible to Fe(III) as the DpmrAB mutant (Table 1) . Collectively, these results strongly suggest that the pmrC, ugd and pmrG genes and the pbgPE operon are the only PmrAregulated determinants required for Fe(III) resistance.",
